      "\n  have h₁ : (∫ x in 0..π, sin x * f (cos x)) = (∫ x in 0..π, sin x * f (cos x)) := rfl\n  have h₂ : (∫ x in 0..π, sin x * f (cos x)) = (∫ y in -1..1, f y) := by\n    have h₃ : (∫ x in 0..π, sin x * f (cos x)) = (∫ x in (0 : ℝ)..π, sin x * f (cos x)) := by\n      simp\n    rw [h₃]\n    have h₄ : (∫ x in (0 : ℝ)..π, sin x * f (cos x)) = (∫ y in -1..1, f y) := by\n      have h₅ : (∫ x in (0 : ℝ)..π, sin x * f (cos x)) = (∫ y in -1..1, f y) := by\n        have h₆ : ∫ x in (0 : ℝ)..π, sin x * f (cos x) = ∫ y in (cos π)..(cos 0), f y := by\n          -- Use the substitution u = cos x, du = -sin x dx\n          have h₇ : ∫ x in (0 : ℝ)..π, sin x * f (cos x) = ∫ x in (0 : ℝ)..π, f (cos x) * sin x := by\n            apply intervalIntegral.integral_congr\n            intro x hx\n            ring\n          rw [h₇]\n          -- Apply the change of variables theorem\n          have h₈ : ∫ x in (0 : ℝ)..π, f (cos x) * sin x = ∫ y in (cos π)..(cos 0), f y := by\n            have h₉ : ∫ x in (0 : ℝ)..π, f (cos x) * sin x = ∫ x in (0 : ℝ)..π, f (cos x) * sin x := rfl\n            rw [h₉]\n            -- Use the substitution u = cos x, du = -sin x dx\n            have h₁₀ : ∫ x in (0 : ℝ)..π, f (cos x) * sin x = ∫ y in (cos π)..(cos 0), f y := by\n              have h₁₁ : ∫ x in (0 : ℝ)..π, f (cos x) * sin x = ∫ x in (0 : ℝ)..π, (f (cos x) * sin x) := rfl\n              rw [h₁₁]\n              -- Apply the change of variables theorem\n              have h₁₂ : ∫ x in (0 : ℝ)..π, (f (cos x) * sin x) = ∫ y in (cos π)..(cos 0), f y := by\n                have h₁₃ : ∫ x in (0 : ℝ)..π, (f (cos x) * sin x) = ∫ y in (cos π)..(cos 0), f y := by\n                  -- Use the substitution u = cos x, du = -sin x dx\n                  have h₁₄ : ∫ x in (0 : ℝ)..π, (f (cos x) * sin x) = ∫ x in (0 : ℝ)..π, (f (cos x) * sin x) := rfl\n                  rw [h₁₄]\n                  -- Apply the change of variables theorem\n                  have h₁₅ : (∫ x in (0 : ℝ)..π, (f (cos x) * sin x)) = ∫ y in (cos π)..(cos 0), f y := by\n                    -- Use the substitution u = cos x, du = -sin x dx\n                    rw [intervalIntegral.integral_comp_cos (fun x => f x)]\n                    <;> simp [cos_zero, cos_pi]\n                    <;> norm_num\n                    <;>\n                    (try ring_nf) <;>\n                    (try norm_num) <;>\n                    (try linarith [Real.pi_pos])\n                  rw [h₁₅]\n                rw [h₁₃]\n              rw [h₁₂]\n            rw [h₁₀]\n          rw [h₈]\n        rw [h₆]\n        -- Simplify the limits of integration\n        have h₇ : (cos π : ℝ) = -1 := by norm_num [Real.cos_pi]\n        have h₈ : (cos 0 : ℝ) = 1 := by norm_num [Real.cos_zero]\n        rw [h₇, h₈]\n        <;> simp [intervalIntegral.integral_symm]\n        <;> ring_nf\n        <;> norm_num\n      rw [h₅]\n    rw [h₄]\n  rw [h₂]",
      "sin(x) dx = -∫_{cos(a)}^{cos(b)} f(y) dy`.\n\nIn our case, `a = 0`, `b = π`, `cos(a) = 1`, `cos(b) = -1`, so:\n`∫_{0}^{π} f(cos(x)) sin(x) dx = -∫_{1}^{-1} f(y) dy = ∫_{-1}^{1} f(y) dy`.\n\nBut Lean likely has this lemma somewhere.\n\nLooking for it in Mathlib:\n`integral_comp_deriv`? Not exactly. \nBut looking at the file `Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Integral/Basic.lean`, there is:\n`intervalIntegral.integral_comp` which requires monotonicity.\nThere is also:\n`integral_comp_mul_left`, but not directly applicable.\n\nBut perhaps not, because our composition is inside the integrand, not the bounds.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps we can use that `cos` is injective on `[0, π]`, and that:\n`∫_{0}^{π} sin(x) f(cos(x)) dx` can be rewritten using the antiderivative of `f(cos(x)) * (-sin(x))`, but this is not straightforward unless we have an explicit antiderivative.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps better:\nUse that `sin(x) dx = -d(cos(x))`, and thus:\n`∫_{0}^{π} sin(x) f(cos(x)) dx = ∫_{0}^{π} f(cos(x)) (-d(cos(x))) = -∫_{0}^{π} f(cos(x)) d(cos(x))`, and this becomes `- [ ∫_{1}^{-1} f(y) dy ]`, because when `x = 0`, `cos(x) = 1`, when `x = π`, `cos(x) = -1`, and `d(cos(x))` is going from `1` to `-1`.\nThus, `-∫_{1}^{-1} f(y) dy = ∫_{-1}^{1} f(y) dy`.\n\nBut perhaps this is too informal.\n\nBut perhaps Lean can use a variant of `interval",
      "how:\n\nWe need to prove that `∫ x in 0..π, sin x * f(cos x) = ∫ y in -1..1, f(y)`.\n\nFirst, notice",
      "\n  have h₁ : ∫ x in 0..π, sin x * f (cos x) = ∫ y in -1..1, f y := by\n    have h₂ : ∫ x in 0..π, sin x * f (cos x) = ∫ x in 0..π, sin x * f (cos x) := rfl\n    rw [h₂]\n    -- Use the substitution y = cos x, dy = -sin x dx\n    -- When x = 0, y = 1; when x = π, y = -1\n    -- The integral becomes ∫ from 1 to -1 f(y) (-dy) = ∫ from -1 to 1 f(y) dy\n    have h₃ : ∫ x in 0..π, sin x * f (cos x) = ∫ y in (cos π)..(cos 0), f y := by\n      have h₄ : ∫ x in 0..π, sin x * f (cos x) = ∫ x in 0..π, sin x * f (cos x) := rfl\n      rw [h₄]\n      -- Use the substitution rule for integrals\n      have h₅ : ∫ x in 0..π, sin x * f (cos x) = ∫ y in (cos π)..(cos 0), f y := by\n        have h₆ : ∫ x in 0..π, sin x * f (cos x) = ∫ y in (cos π)..(cos 0), f y := by\n          rw [intervalIntegral.integral_comp_cos (fun x => f x)]\n          <;> simp [cos_zero, cos_pi]\n          <;> ring_nf\n          <;> norm_num\n          <;> linarith [Real.pi_pos]\n        exact h₆\n      exact h₅\n    rw [h₃]\n    -- Simplify the limits of integration\n    have h₇ : (cos π : ℝ) = -1 := by norm_num\n    have h₈ : (cos 0 : ℝ) = 1 := by norm_num\n    rw [h₇, h₈]\n    <;> simp [intervalIntegral.integral_symm]\n    <;> ring_nf\n    <;> norm_num\n  exact h₁",
      "\n  have h : ∫ x in 0..Real.pi, sin x * f (cos x) = ∫ x in 0..Real.pi, sin x * f (cos x) := rfl\n  rw [h]\n  -- Use the substitution y = cos x, dy = -sin x dx\n  -- When x = 0, y = 1; when x = π, y = -1\n  -- So ∫0^π sin x f(cos x) dx = ∫1^{-1} f(y) (-dy) = ∫-1^1 f(y) dy\n\n  -- Use interval_integral.integral_comp_mul_left_add or similar to make this formal.\n  -- Perhaps use the fact that cos is differentiable on [0, π]\n  -- Or perhaps use that ∫a^b g'(x) f(g(x)) dx = ∫g(a)^g(b) f(y) dy.\n\n  -- Alternatively, we can use the fact that we can find an antiderivative:\n  -- Let G(x) = -F(cos x), then G'(x) = sin x F'(cos x) = sin x f(cos x).\n  -- Then ∫0^π sin x f(cos x) dx = G(π) - G(0) = -F(-1) + F(1) = ∫-1^1 f(y) dy.\n\n  -- But we need to assume that F exists. But we can't construct F generally for any f.\n\n  -- So perhaps better to use the first approach with the substitution.\n  -- But Lean's intervalIntegral doesn't have this directly, so perhaps we need another approach.\n\n  -- Hmm. Another approach is to note that:\n  -- ∫0^π sin x f(cos x) dx is equal to ∫_{cos π}^{cos 0} f(y) (-dy) = ∫_{-1}^{1} f(y) dy.\n  -- But perhaps we can use that cos is decreasing on [0, π], and thus the interval [0, π] maps to [cos π, cos 0] = [-1, 1].\n\n  -- The following works in Lean:\n  have h₁ : ∫ x in (0 : ℝ)..Real.pi, sin x * f (cos x) = ∫ y in (-1 : ℝ)..(1 : ℝ), f y := by\n    -- Use the substitution y = cos x, dy = -sin x dx.\n    -- We use `intervalIntegral.integral_comp_neg` and `intervalIntegral.integral_comp_sub_left` and `intervalIntegral.integral_comp_mul_left_add` to build it.\n    -- But perhaps better to use an additive version of the theorem.\n    -- Alternatively, we can use the fact that the integral of g'(x) f(g(x)) is equal to ∫ f(y) dy from g(a) to g(b).\n\n    -- Let's use the fact that (cos x)' = -sin x. \n    -- Then ∫ sin x f(cos x) dx = -∫ (cos x)' f(cos x) dx = - (F(cos x) |_0^π) where F' = f.\n    -- But this again uses the antiderivative. \n\n    -- Another approach: perhaps actually prove it for step functions and use density?\n    -- Not the best approach, perhaps.\n\n    -- Another approach: perhaps use that sin x ≥ 0 on [0, π] and use some approximation. \n    -- But this might require more advanced tools than needed.\n\n    -- Let's try using `intervalIntegral.integral_comp_cos` if it exists?\n    -- It seems not.\n\n    -- Use integration by parts? Doesn't help here.\n\n    -- Let's try instead to show that ∫0^π sin x (f ∘ cos) x dx = ∫-1^1 f y dy by using that `cos` is `C^∞`.\n\n    -- Alternatively, perhaps use the general change of variables formula:\n    -- ∫_{A} f ∘ g |det g'| = ∫_{g(A)} f.\n    -- But this is too general and perhaps not directly relevant here.\n\n    -- Alternatively, realize that Lean might already have this result in some form. \n    -- Indeed, there is a `intervalIntegral.integral_comp_mul_left_add`, but not for trigonometric functions.",
